<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900409-0007</DOCNO><DOCID>900409-0007.</DOCID><HL>   Pact Set for Computer   andamp; Communications,   Competitor to Merge</HL><DATE>04/09/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6A</SO><CO>   CCTC</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   SAN DIEGO -- Financially troubled Computer andamp;Communications Technology Corp. said it agreed in principleto merge with closely held Sunward Technologies, resulting innew, 55% majority control of the company by Sunwardshareholders.   Computer andamp; Communications Technology also disclosed thatit has technically defaulted on $8.7 million of debt and thatit expects to report a $12.4 million fourth-quarter loss,largely because of one-time charges.</LP><TEXT>   Revenue for the latest quarter was about $17.6 million.The loss for 1989 totals about $17.3 milllion on revenue of$61.5 million, the company said.   The proposed merger is subject to shareholder and bankapproval. Both companies make magnetic recording heads forcomputer disk drives and jointly represent about 40% of theworld-wide non-captive market for such products, said GaryHall, chief financial officer of Computer andamp; CommunicationsTechnology. Both companies are based in San Diego.   The merged company will adopt the Sunward Technologiesname. However, Computer andamp; Communications, technically thecontinuing entity, will issue 14.5 million new shares toSunward holders. Computer andamp; Communications Technologycurrently has about 11.3 million shares outstanding.   Everett Bahre, chairman, president, and chief executiveofficer of Computer Communications andamp; Technology, said themerger will &quot;substantially reduce manufacturing and operatingexpenses&quot; as well as add about $6.5 million of cash atSunward to the combined balance sheet. Sunward had revenuelast year of $42.1 million.   Sunward has manufacturing operations in the Philippines,and about 1,500 employees. Computer Communications andamp;Technology, with manufacturing operations in South Korea andPuerto Rico, has about 2,000 employees.</TEXT></DOC>